Yesterday I sent Mezzogiorno di Fuoco, 13d on Punta Giradili. It was the most hard pitches I’ve climbed in a day.
Working on this route built up both my power and endurance. Yesterday morning I warmed up on the 12a, shakily linked the athletic 13d, mustered up the power for the 13c, made a desperate dive on the 13a, then cruised the 12d to pull all the pitches together. Not to mention the final 7a to exit and the runout 11b on pitch 3. This line has a special combination of back-to-back hard pitches with a wild, adventurous style of bolting. It was established by Rolando Larcher, Maurizio Oviglia and Roberto Vigiani and first freed by Rolando in 2007. 

Thanks to all the work that’s being done by route developers out there to establish such beautiful lines.  And thanks to @anikulapu for being the best partner and working it/ climbing it with me. 

@thenorthface @dmm_wales @lasportivagram #climbing #rockclimbing

Reflecting back to 2018 to the summer I lived on the Juneau Ice Cap, searching for Marc… waiting, searching and climbing.
When September rolled around, Gabe Hayden and I committed to the grand adventure up the unclimbed west face of the Devils Paw, Alaska, 1300m.
Topping at sundown, we rappelled into the night navigating a new decent path. Bringing back the memories of deep emotion connected to the loss of Marc and Ryan, here’s a link to a podcast I have about the experience: https://m.soundcloud.com/american-alpine-journal/brette-harrington-and-the-devils-paw-ep-12 

And of course, and article I wrote for the American Alpine Journal: http://publications.americanalpineclub.org/articles/13201215269/Heart-of-the-Mountain

I’ve been keeping these photos secret for far too long now.  But last summer during the heat wave of July i returned  to the elusive Chinese Puzzle Wall to complete a new route and finish off an incomplete project,  the two pitch variation of Hidden Dragon. I had aided this in 2016 with Marc André while opening the route ground up.  It required copper heading and bird beaks. Back then we only had a hand drill, so the option to free these pitches was far too time consuming.  But returning last summer with better rock climbing skills, and a drill, I equipped and  freed them.  Alas, these beautiful images, with many more to come .  Thanks to @nat.macd for all the work and establishment and completion of Cajun Moon, and to @squamish_rock_guides Tony Mclane for returning to the wall.  These photos were taken by @anikulapu who spent 10 days up there with us, shooting all the routes in the heat. 
So much love to all of you.  Now climbers, the time is now!! 

@thenorthface @reelrock @lasportivana @mammutna @dmm_wales 

#climbonma #climbing #chinesepuzzlewall #rockclimbing #beautifulbritishcolumbia

With unusually stormy weather for California this August, @inespapert and I ventured to the western Sierra to try this beautiful 4 pitch route called Trail of Tears, 13c. First freed by Chris Sharma and Melissa LaCasse and established by Shawn Jones and Lonnie Kauk, it had to be a classic :) The recent Bear Creek Fire destroyed the majority of the forests making for challenging and dirty travel.  The route was incredible, and turned out to be the perfect project for the time we had. We both made a complete free ascent of the route and narrowly missed being hit by lightning, and the hurricane.  Thanks for the fun week @inespapert !! 

We didn’t get any nice photos of ourselves so @shawnreeder was kind enough to let me use this epic one he shot of @chris_sharma. website shawnreeder.com

Over the past two months @anikulapu and I have been working on a magnificent climbing project, establishing a new route on the east coast of Sardinia. We were drawn to this cave from the moment we saw it.  We spent many days studying the wall, searching for the most probable line, and strategizing. 
We chose a line that was perhaps going to have sections of impossibility, but we would never truly know until we tried.

The challenges of establishing routes in a cave are immense.  First off, the vegetation blocks many of the holds, so we were often forced to aid climb, gardening above our heads, with plants and dirt falling directly on top of us. 
The cave is a total of 4 pitches, each about 30m, and is wildly overhanging the entire way. 
Pitch 2 shown here, I have finally decided is 8b (13d). I am particularly proud of this pitch as it claims a style that is entirely unique to this route.  I established it by aid rope soloing using wild styles of aid which I had never used before such as lassoing tufa blobs, using countless hook placements, cams and wires.  It was truly one of the coolest pitches of aid I have ever done, then became even more of a miraculous free climb. 
Starting off with an improbable power endurance sequence for the first 15m, to arrive at a knee bar rest, then the latter 15m continue with resistance climbing to reach powerful boulder sequences. 

The line is still incomplete, merely because we ran out of time to clean p3.

We must return to complete it, but thus far, the pitches are as follows:
P1: 7c+ 
P2: 8b
P3: unknown
P4: somewhere between 8a+ and 8b

I’d like to thank all Elliott for all of the hard work, creativity and motivation.  This was our vision and we committed to it.  I’d also like to thank @francesco_cabras_ for so many days of help, from driving, to belaying, to genreral exploration of the area, and @aleksandrataistra for belaying me on p2, our final day to get these shots. @lappasclimbingbolts for supporting us with the highest quality titanium bolts for this marine environment. 
And of course Kitty, joining us on this adventure. 

Until next time Sardinia! 

@thenorthface @lasportivagram @mammutna @lappasclimbingbolts
